🛠 Exercises¶

  1. Write a function to visualize an image from any dataset (train or test file) and any class (e.g. "steak", "pizza"... etc), visualize it and make a prediction on it using a trained model.
  2. Use feature-extraction to train a transfer learning model on 10% of the Food Vision data for 10 epochs using tf.keras.applications.efficientnet_v2.EfficientNetV2B0 as the base model. Use the ModelCheckpoint callback to save the weights to file.
  3. Fine-tune the last 20 layers of the base model you trained in 2 for another 10 epochs. How did it go?
  4. Fine-tune the last 30 layers of the base model you trained in 2 for another 10 epochs. How did it go?

1. Write function to visualize an image from any dataset (train or test) and any class ('steak', 'pizza'), and have it be visualized, with prediction made on it with a trained model¶

Based on what they want us to accomplish, we need the following variables for our function:

  • File directory/location
  • Photo class
  • Model of choice
  1. Use random for random.choice to select a random image from the class that was specified.
  2. Create the image directory path, from the specified directory
  3. Use mpimg.imread to 'read' the image, aka getting it to be displayed
  4. Get inputed model to predict the specified image
  5. Use plt to plot the image, and annotate over the picture with the prediction, and actual label

Before any function creation, I will first write the code out as I would step by step, then aggregate them into a final function, once a desired result is met.

Create directory of data¶

We will use the 10 percent data for directory location, as this is the only directory where I kept the test folder. the 1 percent and all data test folders have been deleted to save storage space, as they are identical to each other.

In [1]:

Create exact model, that the weights are saved to¶

Instead of a simple copy paste situation for the model and it's layers, we've only done the checkpoint of the model, so will have to create the body from scratch again as practice.

In [12]:
# recreate the model to load the weights into
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential

# augmentation layer for training 
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip('horizontal'),
    layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
    layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
    layers.RandomHeight(0.2),
    layers.RandomWidth(0.2),
], name='data_augmentation'
)

# setup input shape
input_shape = (224,224,3)

# create frozen base model layer
base_model = tf.keras.applications.efficientnet_v2.EfficientNetV2B0(include_top=False)
base_model.trainable=False

# create input and output layers
inputs = layers.Input(shape=input_shape, name='input_layer') # create input layer for the incoming images
x = data_augmentation(inputs) # put input shape into data augmentation
x = base_model(x, training=False) # pass augmented images into base_model, which layers are frozen
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_average_pooling_layer')(x) # average pool the results of the image into its colour channels, so it's 1 dimensional and can be passed towards output layer
outputs = layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax', name='output_layer')(x) # output layer, consisting of 10 categories from our problem
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

# compile model
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Test the model, and import image dataset¶

Let's quickly test the model on a random image from the test folder. But to do so, we will also need to import the image dataset, and transpose it correctly, so the model can read it as well.

  • To create train and test, use image_dataset_from_directory() method
  • Create train_data, and label mode is set to categorical, add batch size 32, and image size to (224,224,3)
  • Create test_data like train data, but without batch size
  • Use random.choice to pick a random class, and a random image
  • Use mpimg.imread to read image, and have it be plotted via matplotlib
  • Fit the model on the specific image that was selected, and print it's prediction, with the accompanied true class label

Sweet! Everything has worked. Now it's time to create a function out of what was typed out.

In [ ]:
# create function that calls for data folder (train/test), class name, and chosen model
def predict_image(data, class_name, model):

    target_dir = '10_food_classes_10_percent/' + data + '/' + class_name # create target directory with inputted data type, and class
    random_image = random.choice(os.listdir(target_dir)) # select a random image from said dir
    random_image_path = target_dir + '/' + random_image # create directory location of said random img

    img = mpimg.imread(random_image_path) # read image
    plt.imshow(img) # show image via plt
    plt.axis(False); # remove numbered x and y axis

    processed_img = tf.image.resize(img, (224,224)) # preprocess img for the model to read
    pred = model.predict(tf.expand_dims(processed_img,axis=0)) # image is expanded to fit model's input shape, and is predicted on

    print(f'Prediction of class: {test_data.class_names[pred.argmax()]} \n True class: {class_name}') # print the result with the highest probability out of all classes, and also the true class

3. Fine-tune the last 20 layers of the base model you trained in 2 for another 10 epochs.¶

To do this, we will need to get to the base_model of our model, and unfreeze the last 20 layers of the model. Since the model has been changed, we have to make sure that we compile the model again, or else the changes we've made won't save to the model.

The following steps:

  1. Create variable that indexes to the base_model location
  2. Create for loop function on the last 20 index of layers, where layer.trainable=False, to allow training
  3. compile model, and check model if it was successfully changed with a for loop, and using enumerate function
In [ ]:
# check model layers and see where base model is
model.layers
Out[ ]:
[<InputLayer name=input_layer, built=True>,
 <Sequential name=data_augmentation, built=True>,
 <Functional name=efficientnetv2-b0, built=True>,
 <GlobalAveragePooling2D name=global_average_pooling_layer, built=True>,
 <Dense name=output_layer, built=True>]
In [65]:
# find base model location
base_model_loc = model.layers[2] # base model is at index 2 of model
In [ ]:
# unfreeze last 20 layers, aka top of the model
for layer in base_model_loc.layers[-21:]: # extra index to account for starting number not being included
    layer.trainable=True

# recompile the model to save changes
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001), # adam learning rate dropped 10x to not heavily affect weights that are pre-set on model.
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Let's check the layer's trainable status, by creating a for loop through the entire base model.

In [83]:
# check trainability of layers in base model
for layer_number, layer in enumerate(base_model_loc.layers):
    print(layer_number, layer.name, layer.trainable)

4. Fine-tune the last 30 layers of the base model you trained in 2 for another 10 epochs. How did it go?¶

To this, we will basically repeat what we have done on the above, except for one thing we will have to do before training even begins.

We will need to add back the model checkpoint from when we've completed 10 epochs during feature extraction phase.

In [89]:
# re-add checkpoint of model
model.load_weights(checkpoint_path)

Now we will unfreeze the top 30 layers of base model, and recompile the model to properly save the changes.

In [112]:
# unfreeze the top 30 layers
for layer in base_model_loc.layers[-30:]: # mistake with -21. chose that number cuz that's what gave'20' trainable variable when printing
    layer.trainable=True

# recompile model
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

The graph shows a very similar pattern to the 20 layer fine tune model. Where the training loss and accuracy, overtakes the validation loss and accuracy. Becoming the more accurate option over the other. Again, overfitting may start to play on the model as its getting too good on training, which can stall or even negatively impact the model's learning habits on unseen data, like our validation images.
